1. Update docker-compose.yml
You need to add the node-exporter service. It requires several system-level mounts so it can "look outside" the container and see the real hardware of your AWS instance.

Add this block to your services: section:

YAML
  node-exporter:
    image: prom/node-exporter:latest
    container_name: node-exporter
    volumes:
      - /proc:/host/proc:ro
      - /sys:/host/sys:ro
      - /:/rootfs:ro
    command:
      - '--path.procfs=/host/proc'
      - '--path.rootfs=/rootfs'
      - '--path.sysfs=/host/sys'
      - '--collector.filesystem.mount-points-exclude=^/(sys|proc|dev|host|etc)($$|/)'
    ports:
      - "9100:9100"
    networks:
      - monitoring
    restart: unless-stopped
    deploy:
      resources:
        limits:
          memory: 64M  # Very lightweight
2. Update prometheus.yml
Now, tell Prometheus to start scraping the server hardware data. Add this job to the bottom of your scrape_configs: list:

YAML
  - job_name: 'node-exporter'
    static_configs:
      - targets: ['node-exporter:9100']
3. Apply the Changes
Since you've modified the files, run:

Bash
docker compose up -d
4. Important Queries for Node Exporter
Once the container is up and the target shows as UP in Prometheus (:9090 -> Status -> Targets), try these powerful hardware queries:

Total Free RAM on your AWS Server:

Code snippet
node_memory_MemFree_bytes / 1024 / 1024
Total CPU Usage (All cores):

Code snippet
100 - (avg by (instance) (irate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) * 100)
Available Disk Space (in %):

Code snippet
(node_filesystem_avail_bytes{mountpoint="/"} / node_filesystem_size_bytes{mountpoint="/"}) * 100
Why use Node Exporter if we have cAdvisor?
Think of it this way:

cAdvisor tells you: "Your Django container is using 200MB of RAM."

Node Exporter tells you: "Your entire AWS server only has 50MB of RAM left, and the Hard Drive is 90% full!"




